Problem 2 (20 points) 
(a) Translate into English: 

Hakhun is an SOV (Subject-Object-Verb) language with ergative-absolutive alignment. The verb ends with ne , and pronouns are marked by prefixes. The suffix -m  indicates the plural.   

    nɤ ʒip ku ne    
        ku  (past tense marker) → Did I sleep? 
        → Did I sleep? 
         

    ati kəmə nirum lapkʰi tʰi ne    
        ati  (3rd person singular), nirum  (plural), tʰi  (plural object marker) → Did he see us? 
        → Did he see us? 
         

    tarum kəmə nuʔrum cʰam ran ne    
        tarum  (3rd person plural), nuʔrum  (plural), ran  (plural object marker) → Did they know us? 
        → Did they know us? 
         

    nirum kəmə tarum lan ki ne    
        nirum  (plural), tarum  (plural), lan  (plural object marker) → Do we beat them? 
        → Do we beat them? 
         

    nirum kəmə nɤ cʰam tiʔ ne    
        nirum  (plural), nɤ  (singular), tiʔ  (singular object marker) → Do we know you (sg)? 
        → Do we know you? 
         

    nirum ka tiʔ ne    
        nirum  (plural), tiʔ  (singular object marker) → Do we see him? 
        → Do we see him? 
         
     

(b) Translate into Hakhun: 

    Did I beat yousg?  → nɤ lan ku ne   
    Did they see me?  → tarum kəmə ŋa lapkʰi tʰɤ ne   
    Does he know yousg?  → ati kəmə nɤ cʰam tɤʔ ne   
    Do you_{pl} sleep?  → nuʔrum ka ʒip ne 
     

Problem 3 (20 points) 
(a) Fill in the gaps: 

Terêna shows a CV(C)  syllable structure. The stressed syllable often has lengthening  (marked by ˆ ) and consonant lengthening (marked by ́ ). The 2nd person sg suffix typically begins with p-  or y- .   
