(b) 

    Portuguese borrowings in Terêna  have no nasalization  (unlike native words ending in -m  which nasalize the entire word).  
    My tin can : leátana  → nileátana  (1st person prefix ni-  + leátana ).
    My cloak : keápana  → nikeápana .
     

Problem 4 (20 points) 
(a) Word X is the numeral "one"  (not used in sequences like 1-10, 11-20, etc.). Missing in examples: 6 eggs (2), 26 eggs (11), and 26 betel nuts (10) . Context implies "one" when counting sequentially. 
(b) Translate into English: 

    biabys atub bøbys  → 14 betel nuts   
    atub juhurub  → 10 eggs   
    nybat atuh araruh  → 23 sugar canes   
    biagas atugas biagas baigas  → 20 sheets of sago bark   
    wiwis baigas  → 20 sheets of sago bark 
     

(c) Translate into Mountain Arapesh: 

    4 betel nuts : biabys bøbys   
    11 eggs : atub atugas atug baigas   
    20 eggs : biagas atugas biagas baigas   
    25 sheets : biogu atub wiwis baigas 
     

Problem 5 (20 points) 
(a) Family Tree : 

    Man 1 : Enu → Children: Woman 4 (Thema) and Man 4 (Yaw).  
    Woman 1 : Thema → Child: Man 5 (Kunto).  
    Woman 2 : Ama → Married to Man 2 (Kofi), children: Man 6 (Dubaku) and Woman 6.  
    Man 3 : Kobina → Child: Woman 7 (Efua).  
    Woman 3 : Awotwi → Child: Man 7 (Berko).
     

(b) Fill the gaps: 

    Yaw’s statements :   
        Yɛfrɛ me Yaw. Yɛfrɛ me ɛnanom Dubaku ne Kunto. Yɛfrɛ me banom Thema ne Ama. Yɛfrɛ me nuanom Yaw ne Ama. Yɛfrɛ me yere Awotwi. Yɛfrɛ me agya Ofori. Yɛfrɛ me sewaabanom Esi ne Kofi. Yɛfrɛ me wɔfaase Berko. 
         

    Kunto’s statements :   
        Yɛfrɛ me Kunto. Yɛfrɛ me banom Kofi ne Dubaku. Yɛfrɛ me nuanom Yaw ne Ama. Yɛfrɛ me sewaabanom Kunto ne Efua. 
         
     